<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1930-03-19T17:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1930-03-19T17:00:00-05:00" n="654" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d654">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">693.9431/38: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of
                                    State</gloss> to the Ambassador in Japan</hi> (<persName type="to"><hi rend="italic">Castle</hi></persName>)</head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1930-03-19T17:00:00-05:00">March 19, 1930—5
                                p.m.</date></dateline></opener>
                        <p>51. Your telegram 47 dated March 12 [<hi rend="italic">18</hi>], 4 p.m.
                                [<hi rend="italic">11 a.m.</hi>]</p>
                        <p>Does paragraph “No. 6” refer to a general conference of the
                            representatives of creditors or only to representatives of Japanese
                            creditors? Shanghai press despatch relating to the new agreement states
                            that Japan “induced Nanking to reaffirm the Nishihara loans.”<note n="24" xml:id="d654fn24">So-called; they were unsecured Japanese
                                loans to China during the World War.</note> Have you any information
                            on this point?</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Cotton</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>